<p><ent>Tusk</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Tusk
<hw>Tusk</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>tusk</ets>, the same word as
<ets>tusch</ets>, AS. <ets>tusc</ets>. See <er>Tush</er> a tooth.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>One of the elongated incisor or
canine teeth of the wild boar, elephant, etc.; hence, any long,
protruding tooth.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A toothshell, or Dentalium; --
called also <altname>tusk-shell</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Carp.)</fld> <def>A projecting member like a tenon,
and serving the same or a similar purpose, but composed of several
steps, or offsets. Thus, in the illustration, <it>a</it> is the
<xex>tusk</xex>, and each of the several parts, or offsets, is called a
<xex>tooth</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tusk</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Tusk
<hw>Tusk</hw> <pr>(t⟦ucr⟧sk)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To bare or
gnash the teeth.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tusked</ent>⟦br⟧
